answers.body_markdown:
Yes, you can do it with casting.

Start with your numeric value `0x6dfee8`, perhaps in an `int`:

    int addr = 0x6dfee8;

Actually, let&#39;s change that: `std::uintptr_t` is also an integer, but it&#39;s made for this purpose, as it is guaranteed to have sufficient size and alignment to do the job we need it to do.

    std::uintptr_t addr = 0x6dfee8;

Cool, that&#39;s better.

Now, cast away:

    int* ptr = reinterpret_cast&lt;int*&gt;(addr);

And dereference:

    std::cout &lt;&lt; *ptr &lt;&lt; &#39;\n&#39;;

This technique is useful when you&#39;re coding close to the metal on an embedded system, perhaps hardcoding the address of some memory-mapped register to control a connected piece of hardware without an intervening driver.

Beyond that, it&#39;s not terribly useful (addresses are not portable between processes and, even if they were, the OS would stop you from using them) and you should really avoid it.

